 Avoiding a food problem: private imports and public targeted 
 distribution in Bangladesh after the 1998 flood 
 Carlo del Ninno*, Paul A. Dorosh 
 International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI), 2033 K. Street NW, Washington, DC 20006 1002, USA 
 
 Abstract 
 The 1998 flood in Bangladesh caused a shortfall of 2.2 million tonnes (mill.t) in the rice production and threatened the 
 food security of tens of millions of families. (even though there is the existence of) the best efforts of (people who give money or other things) and the government, the public distribution 
 ofrice and wheat was only 188,000t more than (at first/before other things happened) planned for July 1998 to April1999. 
 However, a major food problem was turned-away as private imports, made possible by trade liberalisation in the early 1990s, 
 stabilised market prices and supplies. The government's direct distribution programs, though small compared to private 
 imports, anyway increased access to food by poor families. Household survey data point to/show that immediate relief 
 efforts were well targeted to flood-affected families, as were moves (from one place to another) from NGOs. (able to be hurt) Group Feeding (VGF), a 
 medium-term program, was not targeted well to families directly exposed to the flood, though the program was (compared to other things) 
 well targeted to poor families. 
 More broadly, the Bangladesh experience with the 1998 flood shows that in a liberalised trade government, where private imports 
 respond to price signals, food aid's (thing that's given/work that's done) to the total availability of food may be (almost nothing/very little). However, foreign help 
 in kind or in cash, can provide useful things/valuable supplies for give money tod, targeted distribution to food-insecure families - help not 
 possible otherwise under tight government budget restrictions. Â© 2001 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 JEL classification: F1; 138; Q18 
 Keywords: Food policy; Food security; Targeting; Trade liberalisation 
 
 1. Introduction 
 The 1998 flood, dubbed 'the flood of the century' 
 in Bangladesh, covered 51% of the country at its peak, 
 caused a shortfall of 2.2 million tonnes (mill.t) in rice 
 production and threatened the food security of tens 
 of millions of families. Government appeals for 
 help in August 1998 created promises of 
 1.083 mill.t of food aid for flood relief and healing/fixing from (people who give money or other things), providing the food grain for an 
 * Corresponding author. 
 E-mail addresses: c.delninno@cgiar.org (C. del Ninno), 
 
 p.dorosh@cgiar.org (P.A. Dorosh). 
 
 (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of targeted public distribution. (even though there is the existence of) the 
 best efforts of (people who give money or other things) and government, the public distribution of rice and wheat was only 188,000t more 
 than (at first/before other things happened) planned for July 1998 to April 1999. 
 Anyway, a major food problem was turned-away. This paper explores how. 
 Unfortunately, food (not enough of something) and hungers are not 
 new to Bangladesh. The great Bengal hunger of 1943 
 killed about three million people in what is now 
 Bangladesh and eastern India (Dreze and Sen, 1989). 
 Drought-related crop failures and a shortage offoreign 
 exchange for impmis resulted in high rice prices and 
 food shortages that added/gave to a sharp increase 
 in death in 1974 (Ravallion, 1990). Major floods 
 
