 in 1987 and 1988, though not leading to a hunger, 
 added/gave to crop shortages and sharp increases in 
 rice prices, lessened by a large increase in public food 
 grain distribution. 
 However, supply (or availability) of food is not the 
 only (thing that decides something) of food security. Food (government money) 
 of families (their legal means and useful things/valuable supplies to get food: own production, other income, public and 
 private moves (from one place to another), and borrowing) decide/figure out their access to food (Sen, 1982). 1 As is described below, the 
 availability of food grains in Bangladesh following the 
 floods of 1998 was maintained mainly through private 
 part/area imports, made possible by trade liberalisation 
 in the early 1990s. Government and NGO programs 
 added/gave mainly by increasing access to food by the 
 poor. 
 Section 2 begins with a review of the food grain 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) of Bangladesh and major changes in government food policy in the 1990s. The effects of the 
 1998 flood on the domestic production and the role of 
 public and (people and businesses that are not part of the government) imports in increasing the 
 supply and stabilising the prices are then discussed. 
 Section 3 focuses on the household access to food, 
 presenting data from a survey of (away from cities) families in 
 flood-affected areas. The analysis focuses on the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of targeting of government programs and the 
 relative (thing that's given/work that's done) of the public, NGO and private 
 moves (from one place to another) in increasing the household access to food. 
 Section 4 ends/decides the discussion. 
 
 2. Food availability after the flood 
 
 Group food availability in Bangladesh is low, 
 even in years of good harvests. In 1996-1997, 
 the latest year of good harvests, total calorie consumption was only 2085 cal per person per 
 day, 72.8% from rice and 9.2% from wheat (FAO 
 Food Balance Sheet, 1997). Three crops of rice 
 are (helped to grow) in Bangladesh: aman, usually transplanted during the bad rainstorms in June-July and collected in November-December; boro, transplanted in 
 December-January and collected in May-June; and 
 1 In fact, the great Bengal hunger was not caused by a crop 
 failure, but was mostly due to an increase in city-based  demand for 
 food during a war-time money-based boom that raised food prices for 
 the (away from cities) poor (Dreze and Sen, 1989). 
 
 aus, often directly spread around in March-April and collected 
 in July-August. Before the 1998 flood, aman and 
 boro rice production in the July 1998 to June 1999 
 money-related year were expected to be 9.5 and 7.8 mill.t, 49 
 and 41%, (match up each pair of items in order), of expected total production 
 of 19.2 mill.t. Due to the adoption of green revolution 
 technology, (including improved seeds, crop-watering/rinsing with water of 
 boro rice in the dry season and fertiliser), rice production has increased quickly, especially since the late 
 1980s, and the country is nearly independent in rice. 
 In the 1990s, rice imports averaged only 686,000 t 
 per year, 4.0% of net rice availability and 3.5% of net 
 food grain availability. Wheat imports (about 64.3% 
 in the form of food aid) averaged 52.9 and 7.7% of 
 net wheat and food grain availability, (match up each pair of items in order) 
 (see Ahmed et al., 2000). 
 Before the April 1994, the liberalisation of (people and businesses that are not part of the government) rice imports (and the 1992liberalisation of 
 (people and businesses that are not part of the government) wheat imports), shortfalls in food grain 
 production were met through food aid, government 
 commercial imports and draw down of public stocks. 
 However, since 1994 the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) imports of rice, 
 mainly from India (which liberalised its (people and businesses that are not part of the government) rice exports in late 1994), have added to the domestic supplies in years of below-average harvests in 
 Bangladesh. So, the import equality price of rice from 
 Indian markets has given a ceiling on rice prices 
 in Bangladesh (Fig. 1). 2 
 The market prices of rice had been high in the first 
 half of 1998, even before the flood, because of a poor 
 1997-1998 aman rice harvest in November/December 
 1997. As domestic prices rose, beginning in December 1997, it became money-making for the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) 
 to import rice from India (mainly by truck and rail 
 across the land borders). Government policy encouraged (people and businesses that are not part of the government) imports of rice by removing the taxes/import taxes on imports, limiting the open market sales, giving 
 instructions to hurry the clearance of rice imports 
 through customs and stopping from the re-(something forced on people/an inconvenient situation) 
 of anti-collecting laws. An excellent boro rice harvest 
 in the mid-1998, brought a (lasting for a short time) (a) break from 
 high prices of rice in Bangladesh, but the prices soon 
 rose again to import equality levels as the flood waters slowly spread across the country from mid-July 
 1998 to early-September 1998. Initial flood damage to 
 2 See Dorosh (200 1) for a more in-depth discussion of the rice 
 trade between India and Bangladesh over the last few years. 
 
