 the standing aus crop was small (only 280,000 t), but 
 the flood also destroyed seedlings for the following 
 November's aman rice crop, (in the end) leading to a 
 1.76 mill.t aman crop loss (Table 1). However, private 
 part/area imports went beyond 200,000 t of rice per month 
 from August 1998 to April1999, totalling 2.377 mill.t 
 over this period, more than offsetting the guessed 
 total rice production shortfall of 2.2 mill.t. 3 
 In comparison to the (people and businesses that are not part of the government) rice and wheat 
 imports, public distribution of food grain was (compared to other things) small, due to (compared to other things) low wheat stock levels at the time of the flood, uncertainties (related to/looking at/thinking about) 
 food aid (things reaching their destinations), problems with government purchase of rice in (stores around the world) and a perceived 
 need to maintain (good) enough stocks to help stabilise markets in the event of possible extreme (for only a short time) shortages. 4 Although rice distribution was greater than 
