 (at first/before other things happened) planned in the months immediately following the flood (July-September), rice distribution was 
 cut back once the food aid wheat became available, 
 partly because international purchase through open 
 tenders did not get the desired amounts. (in the end), only 399,000 t of rice was distributed from 
 July 1998 to April1999, 333,000t less than (at first/before other things happened) 
 programmed in the pre-flood distribution plan. Private 
 part/area rice imports, equal to 2.42 mill.t in this period 
 (using official Government of Bangladesh (GOB) figures), were this way 6.1 times larger than government rice 
 distribution. 5 
 Increased inflows of food aid did enable a large 
 increase in the public distribution of wheat from 
 905,000t to an (happening sometime in the future)  1.603 mill.t for the whole 
 July 1998 to June 1999 money-related year, but in November 1998 wheat distribution was limited by the slow 
 (the act of reaching a destination) of food aid and low government stocks. The 
 big part of public distribution of food grain during 
 and after the flood was not one of increasing total 
 supplies but rather one of targeting relief to those 
 in need. 
