 3. Household access to food: public distribution 
 and other moves (from one place to another) 
 Two major channels ruled government food 
 relief efforts following the flood: unnecessary relief 
 (GR), designed to provide emergency relief to disaster victims; and (able to be hurt) group feeding (VGF), 
 aimed at helping the families over a longer period 
 ((in the end), from September 1998 to April 1999). 6 
 Immediate (for only a short time) relief through GR was targeted 
 by location. In contrast, the VGF program included all 
 the areas of the country (both flooded and non-flood 
 affected areas), and was (related to managers) targeted 
 to poor families through selection by local (groups that decide or promote things) (Del Ninno and Roy, 1999a). However, the 
 sizes of these programs were limited, both by the 
 available wheat stocks (up to early November when 
 the government commercial imports and food aid (things reaching their destinations) added to government stocks) and the (money-related) 
 cost of the programs (covered mostly by 
 food aid). 
 Major flood relief efforts began with the provision 
 of 20,400 t of rice through GR in the flood-affected 
 thanas in August 1998 and an added 30,800 t 
 of rice in September. Also, the VGF program 
 began on a large scale in August with an initial 
 distribution of 1.3 million cards, each entitling the 
 holder to 8 kg of rice per month. During August 
 and September, a total of 27,500 t of rice were distributed through this program. At 8 kg per card, an 
 guessed 1.35 and 2.13 million families received 
 the VGF (gives out portions) in August and September, (match up each pair of items in order). Almost no wheat was distributed through relief channels in the first months of the flood. At 
 the asking of the World Food Programme (WFP), 
 the GOB expanded the VGF program to 4 million 
 cards with an portion of 16 kg of grain per card, 
 half rice and half wheat in October, and all wheat 
 after that. 
 Data from a survey of 757 families conducted 
 in November-December 1998 (about 2.5 months after 
 the floodwaters had moved back) in seven flood-affected 
 thanas were used to provide (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of the extent to 
 6 Food For Work (FFW) programs began on a large scale only 
 in December 1998, following the aman rice harvest, when soils 
 were dry enough to permit manual earthwork in the building of 
 roads and water channels. 
 
 341 
 
 which the GRand VGF programs were well targeted. 7 
 As shown in Table 2, average per person monthly expenses during the period of 15 July to 14 November 1998 were only 755.2 Taka (US$_$ 15.64 at the 
 November 1998 exchange rate of 48.3 Taka per US$_$). 
 Sixty-eight percent of all the families, and 85.5% 
 of the families in the lowest per person expense 
 quintile, owned less than 0.5 areas of land (0.20 ha) of land. 
 A total of 67.1% of the families in the first 
 quintile received some type of government move (from one place to another), 38.8% of these families received VGF grain 
 (mainly wheat) and 31.6% received GR grain (mainly 
 rice). VGF was fairly well-targeted by expense. 
 Anyway, 17.2 and 11.2% of the families in 
 the top two quintiles were people (who were part of a study, etc.). However, the 
 size of these moves (from one place to another) was (compared to other things) small. The average value of VGF grain received by the participating 
 families in October and November 1998 was 202.0 
 Taka per household per month, equal to only 5.0% of 
 total household expenses. For VGF people (who were part of a study, etc.) in 
 the lowest quintile, these moves (from one place to another) were more significant, equal to 10.5% of total household expenses. 
 Table 3 presents data on household expenses and 
 moves (from one place to another) according to an index of household exposure 
 to the flood. This index measures the direct exposure 
 to the flood at the household level, taking into account 
 four factors: (1) the depth of water in the home; 
 (2) the depth of water in the house; (3) the length of time 
 (number of days) of water in the house; and (4) the 
 number of days away from home due to the flood. 
 For each of these four parts/pieces, we created an 
 index ranging from 0 to 5. The total flood exposure 
 index, equal to the sum of the part-related (numbers that change/things that change), 
 ranges in value from 0 to 18. Finally, a categorical 
 (number or thing that changes) was defined according to the value of the flood 
 exposure index: 0 =not exposed to the flood, 1-5 = 
 7 The seven flood-affected thanas, representing five out of six 
 divisions of the country, were selected according to two major 
 judging requirements: the extreme harshness of flood as figured out by/decided by the Water Board 
 and the percentage of poor people in the district in which the 
 thana is located. Given these two major judging requirements, some thanas that 
 were in the samples of earlier studies were purposively selected. 
 Families were randomly selected using a multiple stage chance sampling way of doing things (with the exception of families in one 
 thana that were in the sample of an earlier study). In all, about six families were selected per village, 36 per union, 
 and 108 per thana, for a final sample size of 757 families in 
 126 villages (see Del Ninno and Roy, 1999b, for a more described/explained 
 description of the sampling frame). 
 
