 not highly related to flood exposure and it is 
 important/famous that the poorest 20% of families received 
 only about 115 as much moves (from one place to another) per household (23.8 
 Taka per month) as did the average household in the 
 sample 121.5 Taka per month (see Table 2). 
 The analysis of the (things that decide other things) of participation in 
 GR and VGF programs, conducted using probit (moving backwards), provide further (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of the degree to 
 which these programs were targeted towards the poor 
 
 and flood-exposed families (Table 4). The (moving backwards) clearly show that the judging requirements used for targeting 
 the families with respect to the level of flood exposure varied between the programs. Dummy (numbers that change/things that change) 
 for flood exposure, and especially dummy (numbers that change/things that change) 
 for extreme and very bad flood exposure, are highly 
 significant explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) for the participation 
 in GR. In contrast, flood-exposure (numbers that change/things that change) are not 
 (meaningful numbers) explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) for the 
 participation in VGF, even in this sample of families from flood-affected thanas. 
 The coefficients of the (numbers that change/things that change) that point to/show the 
 level of household wealth confirm that the VGF program was better targeted towards the poorer families. Landlessness and housing (features/ qualities/ traits) (tin 
 roof and the number of buildings in the household 
 compound) are (meaningful numbers) explanatory 
 (numbers that change/things that change) for participation in VGF. However, in the 
 GR moving backward among the household wealth (numbers that change/things that change), 
 only living in a house with a tin roof reduces the 
 chance of participation. 
