 ity of receiving either GR or VGF moves (from one place to another). In the 
 case of GR, this is to be expected, since the flood is 
 likely to have affected all the families in a village, 
 ignoring household size. Anyway, there 
 appears to be a bias in the GR distribution towards 
 smaller families that have fewer younger children, 
 maybe because these families were more mobile 
 and had easiery reaching the distribution centres. In the case of VGF moves (from one place to another), targeting towards 
 larger families with more children might be expected. 
 However, few household (combination of different substances, objects, people, etc.) (numbers that change/things that change) are 
 significant, apart from those for the number of young 
 males, this way pointing to/showing that the overall level of wealth 
 (as reflected in the housing (numbers that change/things that change) discussed above) 
 was the main (thing that decides something) of participation in the 
 VGF program. Somewhat surprisingly, there is only 
 weak (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of targeting towards female-headed 
 families. The coefficient on the dummy (number or thing that changes) 
 for female household head is positive, but it is very different from 0 only at a 17% confidence 
 level. 
 
 4. Ending/deciding (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) 
 Food security at the household level depends both 
 on availability of food in markets and on access to 
 food. 9 Liberalisation of (people and businesses that are not part of the government) imports of rice 
 and wheat in the early 1990s and resulting government policies supporting the trade in 1998, enabled 
 private imports to stabilise market prices and supplies 
 during the 1998 flood in Bangladesh. Government 
 direct distribution programs, though small compared 
 to private imports, anyway increased the access 
 to food by poor families. Given the tight useful thing/valuable supply restrictions that limit the size of distribution 
 programs, effective targeting is important. Immediate 
 relief efforts were well-targeted to flood-exposed 
 families, as were moves (from one place to another) from NGOs. VGF, a 
 medium-term program covered non-flood affected areas and, even in flood-affected thanas, was not targeted well to families directly exposed to the flood. 
 Anyway, according to survey data from the seven 
 flood-affected thanas, the program was (compared to other things) 
 well-targeted to poor families, with families in 
 9 Use, another aspect of food security, is not covered in 
 this paper. 
 
 345 
 
 the three lowest expense quintiles rece1vmg an 
 guessed 75% of the food grain distributed through 
 this program. 
 More broadly, the Bangladesh experience with the 
 1998 flood illustrates the dual role of food aid in 
 increasing the availability and providing useful things/valuable supplies 
 that improve the access of food insecure families. In a liberalised trade government, where private 
 imports respond to price signals, food aid's (thing that's given/work that's done) to total availability of food may be (almost nothing/very little). 
 Anyway, foreign help in kind or in cash 
 can provide useful things/valuable supplies for give money tod, targeted distribution to food-insecure families - help not 
 otherwise possible under tight government budget 
 restrictions. 
 
